Echelon form #define
...

A matix is said to be in (row) Echelon form if the number of zeros preceding the first nonzero entry in each row strictly increases row by row.

Pivot #define:
...

Let the first nonzero entry in a given row be the pivot or distinguish element for that row.
Then if a mtrix is in row echelon form, the pivots move strictly rightwards as we move down the matrix, until we possibly have anumber of zero rows at the end.

#Note The third example amtrix is a special case of row echelon matrix: Reduced row echelon form.

Reduced row echelon form #define
...

A matrix is in reduced row echelon form if:

  1. It is in row echelon form
  2. If all of the pivot element are equal to 1.
  3. If all of the pivot element are only nonzero element in their columns.
